{"analytics_identifier":null,"base_path":"/government/history/past-prime-ministers/george-grenville","content_id":"425e37e1-2b6e-4af5-b82f-4352b1dda89d","description":"“A wise government knows how to enforce with temper, or to conciliate with dignity.”","details":{"body":"<div class=\"govspeak\"><p>George Grenville came from a family of politicians. He became First Lord of the Treasury during a period of considerable political turbulence in the 1760s.</p>\n\n<p>His imposition of new duties on the American colonies helped provoke the outbreak of the American War of Independence.</p>\n\n<p>Read more about George Grenville on the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://history.blog.gov.uk/2015/02/11/george-grenville-whig-1763-1765/\" class=\"govuk-link\">History of government blog</a>.</p>\n</div>","born":"14 October 1712, Wotton, Buckinghamshire","dates_in_office":[{"end_year":1765,"start_year":1763}],"died":"13 November 1770, Bolton Street, Piccadilly, London","interesting_facts":"","major_acts":"The Navy Act 1758: to speed up the payment of seamen’s wages and enable them to send a portion home to their families.  \r\n\r\nThe Stamp Act 1765: required all legal documents, licenses, commercial contracts, newspapers, pamphlets, and playing cards to carry a tax stamp. \r\n\r\nThe Parliamentary Elections Act 1770 - aka The Grenville Act: transferred the power of trying election petitions from the House of Commons to a small committee of MPs selected by lot. ","political_party":"Whig"},"document_type":"historic_appointment","first_published_at":"2023-01-19T17:38:35+00:00","links":{"available_translations":[{"api_path":"/api/content/government/history/past-prime-ministers/george-grenville","api_url":"https://www.gov.uk/api/content/government/history/past-prime-ministers/george-grenville","base_path":"/government/history/past-prime-ministers/george-grenville","content_id":"425e37e1-2b6e-4af5-b82f-4352b1dda89d","document_type":"historic_appointment","links":{},"locale":"en","publi